The skies gleam metallic, the terrain desolate,
Devastation pervades the landscape's stark state;
A feeble stream lingers on mud-caked ground,
Where salt springs bubble and quagmires resound;
The Darling River laments its futile embrace,
Struggling against drought, losing its race;
Attempting to nourish the land far and wide,
Yet thwarted by drainage and nature's dry tide;
Dreaming of bustling banks, verdant scenes,
Children playing, life flowing through its means;
But only bleached bones and demons remain,
Mocking the river's perpetual, desperate strain.

Investigating neutrinoless double-beta decay (0{
u}{ eta}{ eta}) demands minimal background and comprehensive knowledge of its sources and impacts on the parameter space relevant to the 0{
u}{ eta}{ eta} signal. This study examines { eta}- and {\gamma}-backgrounds in the EXO-200 liquid-xenon-based 0{
u}{ eta}{ eta} experiment. The research aims to identify and assess specific background sources, comparing findings with radioassay results from pre- and during-construction periods. The implications for EXO-200 and the future nEXO tonne-scale detector are also explored.
